  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. It is widely recognized as a criminal offense in virtually all jurisdictions around the world.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **International Standards**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF), an intergovernmental organization, sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Most countries have adopted these standards into their legal systems.\n\n2. **National Laws**: Nearly every country has enacted specific legislation to criminalize money laundering. In the United States, for example, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act include provisions to combat money laundering. In the European Union, the Anti-Money Laundering Directives provide a comprehensive legal framework.\n\n3. **Global Cooperation**: Countries cooperate through various international agreements and organizations to combat money laundering. This includes mutual legal assistance treaties (MLATs) and the sharing of financial intelligence through entities like the Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units.\n\n4. **Consequences**: The penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines, imprisonment, and the seizure of assets. Financial institutions that fail to comply with anti-money laundering (AML) regulations can also face significant penalties and reputational damage.\n\n5. **Corporate Compliance**: Businesses, especially financial institutions, are required to implement robust AML programs to detect and report suspicious activities. This includes customer due diligence (CDD), ongoing monitoring, and reporting of large or unusual transactions.\n\nWhile the specifics of laws and enforcement mechanisms may vary from one country to another, the fundamental principle that money laundering is illegal is universally accepted. Efforts to combat money laundering are seen as essential to maintaining the integrity of financial systems and preventing crime.",
